# Quick Launch Steps
## Introduction
Here we will walk you thru the steps to quickly set up the Haptik SDK.
### Minimum and Taget SDK versions of the Haptik SDK
`minSdkVersion 16`

`targetSdkVersion 26`

## **Step 1** Adding `AmazonPay.aar` as a dependency
To allow your users to be able to make payments via the Haptik SDK the AmazonPay sdk will need to be added as a dependency. Incase you don't want to use the payments feature of the Haptik SDK you can ignore this step.

To add this dependency as a module in your project please follow the below steps.

- Right click on the project and select New > Module

![LOGO](data:image/png;base64,)

- Now select `Import .JAR/.AAR Package` and click `Next`

![LOGO](data:image/png;base64,)

- Choose the `AmazonPay.aar` file which was shared with you by the Haptik team and name the subproject what ever you like in this example we have named it `PayWithAmazon`, and click on `Finish`

![LOGO](data:image/png;base64,)
Now please do a Gradle Sync ![LOGO](data:image/png;base64,) and run your app to make sure everything is working correctly. 

## **Step 2** Changes to `build.gradle` for the root project and the app
The first thing we are going to do here is add the following lines of code to your projects **root** `build.gradle` it will be added under allprojects > repositories
```java
maven {
            url "http://artifactory.hellohaptik.com:8081/artifactory/libs-release-local"
            credentials {
                username '[ENTER YOUR USERNAME HERE]'
                password '[ENTER YOUR PASSWORD HERE]'
            }
        }
maven {
            url "http://phonepe.bintray.com/PhonePeThinAndroidSDK"
            credentials {
                username 'phonepe_android_thinsdk_release_key@phonepe'
                password '86d00df8714755cbfa84eb829f69c72fd6203c9c'
            }
        }
maven { url "http://tilsdk.indiatimes.com/nexus/content/groups/public/" }
```

Haptik will provide required username and password while providing access to the SDK.

Once this is done you can move over to your app's `build.gradle` file and add the following lines of code:

```java
compile 'ai.haptik.android.sdk:haptiklib-cab:[VERSION NO]'
```
Use this version when you want to use the cabs feature of the Haptik SDK
```java
compile 'ai.haptik.android.sdk:haptiklib-payment:[VERSION NO]'
```
Use this if you want to use the payments feature of the Haptik SDK
```java
compile 'ai.haptik.android.sdk:haptiklib-core:[VERSION NO]'
```
Use this version incase you don't want to use either Cabs or Payment features of Haptik

Most of the Haptik SDK users want to use both the cabs and payment features of the Haptik SDK in which case you should copy paste the below lines of code:

```java
compile 'ai.haptik.android.sdk:haptiklib-cab:[VERSION NO]'
compile 'ai.haptik.android.sdk:haptiklib-payment:[VERSION NO]'
```
Now here you should run a gradle sync it's possible that SDK and the Host app specify common dependencies, which might result in compile failure on the grounds of class duplication. In such cases specify resolutionStrategy on your App's build.gradle as follows: 

```java
configurations . all {
    resolutionStrategy {
        force < path to your version of conflicting library - 1>
        force < path to your version of conflicting library - 2>
    }
}
```

## **Step 3** Adding Metadata and an Activity to the Manifest
We will now start adding MetaData to the apps Manifest file. This MetaData corresponds to the SDK's:
### API Key
```xml
<meta-data android:name="ai.haptik.android.sdk.ApiKey"
    android:resource="@string/haptik_sdk_api_key"/>
```
Please make sure you save the Haptik API in your `strings.xml` file and refernce it here. 
### Client ID
```xml
<meta-data android:name="ai.haptik.android.sdk.ClientId"
    android:resource="@string/haptik_sdk_client_id"/>
```
Please make sure you save the Haptik Client ID in your `strings.xml` file and refernce it here. 
### Base Url
```xml
<meta-data android:name="ai.haptik.android.sdk.BaseUrl"
    android:resource="@string/haptik_sdk_base_url"/>
```
Please make sure you save the Base Url in your `strings.xml` file and refernce it here. 
### Drawable to be used for showing the Large Notification Icon
```xml
<meta-data android:name="ai.haptik.android.sdk.NotificationIconLarge"
    android:resource="@drawable/ic_notification_large"/>
```
You can use whatever icon best suits your app for this purpose
### Drawable to be used for showing the Small Notification Icon
```xml
<meta-data android:name="ai.haptik.android.sdk.NotificationIconSmall"
    android:resource="@drawable/ic_notification_small"/>
```
You can use whatever icon best suits your app for this purpose

### CleverTap credentials
Haptik uses CleverTap to see how users are engaging with the Haptik SDK and then send the Push Notifications when neccessary
```xml
<meta-data android:name="CLEVERTAP_ACCOUNT_ID"  
     android:value="WILL BE PROVIDED BY HAPTIK"/>  
<meta-data android:name="CLEVERTAP_TOKEN"
    android:value="WILL BE PROVIDED BY HAPTIK"/>
```

### PhonePe AppId
This will be needed to enable PhonePe in the Haptik SDK, failure to add this MetaData tag can result in crashes in your app.
```xml
<meta-data
        android:name="com.phonepe.android.sdk.AppId"
        android:value="WILL BE PROVIDED BY HAPTIK" />
```

### ChatActivity

The following Activity needs to be added to your Manifest. Adding a parent will make sure that the UP button in the ChatActivity will take the user to the correct activity. If you implement an Activity which will host the InboxView then that would be the ideal candidate to be the parent of the ChatActivity.
```xml
<activity android:name="ai.haptik.android.sdk.messaging.ChatActivity" android:parentActivityName="ENTER THE ACTIVITY YOU WANT AS THE PARENT HERE">
    <meta-data android:name="ai.haptik.android.sdk.messaging.backAsUp" android:value="true"/>
</activity>
```

The meta-data tag which is part of the ChatActivity is used to define the behaviour of the back button when the user is in the ChatActivity. There are two possible behaviours that can be assigned to the back button:  
 - The back button will behave the same way as the up button  
 - The back button will follow the default Android behaviour of a back button.  

For the first option the **value** field needs to be set to true and for the second option it needs to
be set to false. Incase you dont add this meta-data tag the value is set to true.

## **Step 4** Init the Haptik SDK
It is recommeneded that the Haptik SDK be initialized in the Apps Application class. In the OnCreate method of the Application class.

If you want to use the SDK in debug mode please add the following line.
```java
HaptikLib.setDebugEnabled(true);
```

If you are pointing the SDK to the Staging Enviroment please add the following line.
```java
HaptikLib.setRunEnvironment(HaptikLib.RUN_ENVIRONMENT_STAGING);
```
By default the SDK is pointing to the Production Environment.

To initialize the SDK you will need to create Haptik's InitData object. You can create that by coping the below code.

```java
InitData initData = new InitData.Builder(application)
            .baseUrl("https://staging.hellohaptik.com")
            .clientMainActivityClass(InboxActivity.class)
            .apiOptions(CabApiFactory.getCabApi())
            .apiOptions(PaymentApiFactory.getPaymentApi())
            .debugEnabled(true)
            .notificationSound(R.raw.notification_sound)
            .build();
```
To learn more about the InitData object please look at the SDK's JAVADOC.

With this `initData` object you can pass it into the `HaptikLib.init(initData)` method to initialize the Haptik SDK.

The SDK **MUST** be initialized before using any of Haptik's functionality. 

## **Step 5** Initial Sync
Check if haptik's initial data has been sync once or not. It's important to sync the initial data once before doing anything because otherwise sdk won't have any data to show on inbox. Once initial data is fetched, there is no need to call this method again because sdk will then handle syncing data internally. **It is advised that you perform the initial sync before signing up the user** 

```java
        if (!DemoPrefUtils.hasHaptikInitialDataSyncDone(this)) {
            HaptikLib.performInitialDataSync(new Callback<Boolean>() {
                @Override
                public void success(Boolean result) {
                    // On Success - set the flag to true so that we don't call this method in next app launch
                    DemoPrefUtils.setHaptikInitialDataSyncDone(ClientActivity.this, true);
                    // Now you can go ahead and sign up the user
                }

                @Override
                public void failure(HaptikException exception) {
                    toggleUiState(false);
                    // Handle Failure - If this fails then you cannot start Haptik. May call performInitialDataSync again
                    Toast.makeText(ClientActivity.this, "Haptik Init Data Sync Failed.\nCan't move ahead!", Toast.LENGTH_SHORT).show();
                }
            });
        } else {
            // Now you can go ahead and sign up the user or if the user is signed up then take them to the inbox page.
        }
```

## **Step 6** Basic Sign Up on the Haptik SDK

Haptik has different types of authentication methods. To get started quickly you can try the Basic Authentication type. But for your app please check out the complete Integration guide to see what Authentication method will suit your app.

Below is the code to sign up the user and start using the Haptik SDK.

```java
SignUpData signUpData = new SignUpData
             .Builder(SignUpData.AUTH_TYPE_BASIC)
             .build();
HaptikLib.signUp(signUpData, new Callback<User>() {
             @Override
             public void success(User result) {
                 Toast.makeText(ClientSignUpActivity.this, "SignUp success", Toast.LENGTH_SHORT).show();
                 // On SignUp success, open inbox activity
             }
 
             @Override
             public void failure(HaptikException exception) {
                 Toast.makeText(ClientSignUpActivity.this, "SignUp failure", Toast.LENGTH_SHORT).show();
                 // Handle SignUp failure, Haptik/inbox must not be opened
                 exception.printStackTrace();
             }
         });
```

## **Step 7** Set up the Inbox
To set up the Inbox please create an Activity which you will want to use as the InboxActivity. This InboxActivity will have an InboxView. The InboxView is a custom view built by Haptik.

This custom view takes care of showing banners and the channels list in the UI. Takes custom styleable-attributes individually to decide whether to show banner or not. If attributes are not specified in xml, the default implementation assumes false for these values.

You must call lifecycle methods of this view in order to populate this view correctly from your Fragment or Activity's related lifecycle methods. Two lifecycle methods for this view are onResume() and onPause().

Below is an example of what your layout file for the InboxActivity will look like.

```xml
<LinearLayout       xmlns:android="http://schemas.android.com/apk/res/android" xmlns:custom="http://schemas.android.com/apk/res/com.example">
<ai.haptik.android.sdk.inbox.InboxView
          android:layout_width="match_parent"
          android:layout_height="wrap_content"
          custom:showBanner="true"/>
</LinearLayout>
```

## **Step 8** Set up GCM
Set the Device Token for FCM on the Haptik Library
```java
// For FCM use
HaptikLib.setFcmDeviceToken(this, refreshedToken);

// For GCM use
HaptikLib.setGcmDeviceToken(this, refreshedToken);
```
Disable Notifications
Enables or disables notification (probably being triggered from your app settings).

```java
Haptik.setNotificationEnabled(boolean enabled) // default is true
```

Make sure you provide your main activity reference via below method. Its strongly recommended to call this from Application class, as it would be needed to be used in every app runtime

Pass any FCM payloads from your FCMMessagingService to the Haptik Notification Manager
```java
final Map<String, String> data = remoteMessage.getData();
        if (HaptikNotificationManager.isHaptikNotification(data)) {
            if (!HaptikLib.isInitialized()) {
                Handler mainHandler = new Handler(getApplicationContext().getMainLooper());
                mainHandler.post(new Runnable() {
                    @Override
                    public void run() {
                        // FIRST INIT HAPTIK SDK AS SHOWN IN STEP 4
                        HaptikNotificationManager.handleNotification(getApplicationContext(), data);
                    }
                });
            } else {
                HaptikNotificationManager.handleNotification(getApplicationContext(), data);
            }
        }
```

For GCM, pass any payloads from your GCMMessagingService to the Haptik Notification Manager
 ```java
     if (HaptikNotificationManager.isHaptikNotification(bundle)) {
          if (!HaptikLib.isInitialized()) {
              HaptikLib.init((AppApplication) getApplicationContext());
          }
          HaptikNotificationManager.handleNotification(getApplicationContext(), bundle);
    }
```
